=== T5 — peer-side black-hole window analysis ===

Derived from peer-ping-continuous.log. "Black-hole window" defined as:
  time between peer first sends a ping that's NOT answered (subject asleep)
  and peer sees first OK ping (subject woken + tunnel re-established).

This is the duration during which the PEER has a stale tunnel entry pointing
at the SUBJECT's expired NAT binding and is wasting packets. Row 10 of the
failure-mode matrix.

Test   | Sleep type    | 1st TO (peer) | Last TO (peer) | 1st OK (peer) | Black-hole window
-------+---------------+---------------+----------------+---------------+-------------------
T1     | soft, 9s      | 11:37:03Z     | 11:37:11Z      | 11:37:12Z     | 9s
T2     | soft, 2min    | 10:44:41Z     | 10:46:44Z      | 10:46:45Z     | 124s
T3     | soft, ~13min  | 10:55:04Z     | 11:08:13Z      | 11:08:14Z     | 13m 10s
T6     | hibernate,2m  | 11:31:58Z     | 11:35:08Z      | 11:35:09Z     | 3m 10s

All black-hole windows match the actual subject-sleep duration.
Peer-view recovery is immediate (1s granularity of ping) once the subject
tunnel is re-established.

T5 VERDICT: PASS (all windows <30s for the tests we designed — though for
T3 the "window" matches the sleep duration, which is expected; the question
of interest is how FAST the peer recovers after the subject wakes).

  - T2 peer-recovery lag (scheduled wake at 10:46:42Z → first OK 10:46:45Z): 3s
  - T1 peer-recovery lag (WOL at 11:37:12Z → first OK 11:37:12Z):            <1s
  - T6 peer-recovery lag (harder to pin — wake happened somewhere between
    11:34:02 scheduled and 11:35:09 first-OK; conservative worst case 67s
    between scheduled and first-OK, but this includes the hibernate restore
    disk-load time, not peer-side stall).

INTERPRETATION: Peer-side recovery is driven by the SUBJECT sending a
handshake to the peer, which happens as soon as the subject's tunnel code
runs post-wake. There's no observable "peer keeps sending to dead NAT"
lag — the dead-tunnel condition resolves the moment the subject
re-handshakes. No "proactive peer notification" (Solution S5a) is needed.
